## AI Agent Workflow

### Codex CLI Role

Codex CLI loads this file natively (no `@import` needed). Defaults to `gpt-5` as of 2026. Good fit: precise diff-style edits, deterministic code transformations, well-specified sub-tasks where ~5 prompt constraints fully define the work.

### Gemini CLI Role

Gemini CLI loads this file via `@./AGENTS.md` import in `GEMINI.md`. Good fit: long-context reads (large diffs / file scans), Google Workspace via `gws` CLI, multimodal (image / PDF) input, small-scoped bugfixes with clear acceptance tests. Gemini does NOT follow symlinks at the `GEMINI.md` path (issue #11547, closed `not_planned` 2025-11-21) — keep `GEMINI.md` as a real file, not a symlink.

### Branch & Push Rules (applies to all delegated CLIs)

PR flow, not direct push to `main`:

1. Agent works on a feature branch named `<cli>/<task-slug>` (e.g. `codex/cleanup-imports`, `gemini/redesign-empty-state`).
2. Before committing, agent runs and confirms green: typecheck + lint commands defined in "Build, Test, and Development Commands" below. For DB-touching work, also run any DB verification command.
3. Commit using conventional style (`feat(scope): ...`, `fix(scope): ...`, etc.) with `Co-Authored-By: <CLI> <noreply@<vendor>.com>` trailer (`<noreply@openai.com>` for Codex, `<noreply@google.com>` for Gemini).
4. Push the branch to origin and open a PR against `main`. Title = the conventional commit title. Body = what changed, what was tested, what the spec said.
5. Do **NOT** self-merge. Wait for human review (or Claude orchestrator in multi-CLI setup).
6. **Do NOT deploy from a feature branch.** Deploys happen post-merge from `main`, by the user or by Claude as orchestrator. Branch-deploy causes `main` ↔ prod desync (any later main-deploy reverts the agent's work).

### Multi-CLI Parallel Workflow

When running Codex and Gemini (or any 2+ CLIs) concurrently on the same repo, give each CLI its own worktree to avoid shared-state conflicts:

```bash
# Standard layout — run from inside the main worktree:
git worktree add ../<project>-codex codex/<task-branch>
git worktree add ../<project>-gemini gemini/<task-branch>
```

Then launch each CLI in its own directory. The main worktree (`<project>/`) stays reserved for Claude (orchestration, review, merge, post-merge deploy).

**Why:** When CLIs share a worktree, one CLI switching branches under the other causes "stale `M file`" panic and stalls execution. Worktrees share git history but each has its own working tree state.

Single-agent rounds (only one CLI at a time) don't need worktree isolation.

**Orchestration brief rule (Claude side):** When writing a delegation brief for Codex or Gemini, the brief's ship section ends at "open PR, wait for review". Do NOT include a deploy command in the brief — let AGENTS.md's "agents don't deploy" rule (above) be canonical. Brief-level deploy instructions risk causing the agent to deploy from its feature branch, creating a branch→prod desync window.

## Tool Preference: CLI over MCP

When a service offers both a CLI and an MCP server, prefer the CLI. Reasons:

- **Token efficiency.** Benchmarks show ~17x fewer tokens per task for CLI vs MCP (Firecrawl / Arize, 2025).
- **Cross-agent auth.** CLI auth lives in `~/.config/<tool>/` and is shared across Claude / Codex / Gemini. MCP OAuth is per-agent.
- **Reliability.** CLI flow is one process call; MCP adds a server hop.

**Preferred CLIs** (install status defaults to `⏳ not installed`; bootstrap user should run `command -v <tool>` per their machine and update to `✓ installed` where applicable):

| Service | Preferred CLI | Install status | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| GitHub | `gh` | ⏳ not installed | Widely installed, mature. |
| Google Workspace (Gmail / Calendar / Drive) | `gws` | ⏳ not installed | Official Google CLI, pre-1.0 as of 2026-05. |
| Google Drive bulk ops | `rclone` | ⏳ not installed | Mature alternative to `gws` for large transfers. |
| Notion | `ntn` | ⏳ not installed | Official, young. |
| Browser scripted flows | Playwright CLI | ⏳ not installed | Mature; use Playwright Python for headless automation. |
| JIRA | `acli` | ⏳ not installed | Atlassian official, GA 2026. |

**Important for sub-agent prompts:** When delegating a task that requires a CLI tool, check this matrix's install status FIRST. For `⏳ not installed`, do one of: (a) ask the user to install before delegating, (b) fall back to the corresponding MCP if available, or (c) use a closer-fit alternative. Do NOT prompt sub-agents (Codex / Gemini) to invoke a tool listed as `⏳ not installed` — they will fail silently or hallucinate output.

### Stay on MCP (no viable CLI)

- **Canva** — no design content management CLI.
- **chrome-devtools** — interactive debug; the CLI surface is too thin.
- **context7** — library docs lookup; the MCP is the primary interface.

